# SecureFlow MCP Dependency Guardrails
# Extends Project CodeGuard (CoSAI/OASIS) with runtime MCP enforcement.
# Place alongside .windsurf/rules/ generated by codeguard-setup.sh.
#
# CodeGuard already covers code-level security standards (parameterized
# queries, input validation, CSRF, secret handling, OWASP Top 10).
# These rules are NOT duplicated here — only the MCP-specific
# dependency guardrails that CodeGuard cannot enforce on its own.

## Dependency Management — MCP-Enforced

- ALWAYS call the `secureflow.check_package` MCP tool BEFORE adding any
  new dependency to package.json, pom.xml, build.gradle, requirements.txt,
  go.mod, Gemfile, or Cargo.toml.
- NEVER suggest a dependency version older than 12 months.
- NEVER introduce a dependency with known CRITICAL or HIGH CVEs.
- PREFER dependencies already in the project's approved catalog
  (`secureflow.list_approved_packages`).
- If `check_package` returns NEEDS_REVIEW, call `request_package` and tell
  the developer that security review is required before the dep can be added.
- If it returns BLOCKED, do NOT add the dependency. Suggest the alternatives
  returned by the tool.
- If it returns PENDING, do NOT add the dependency. Inform the developer that
  approval is already in progress.

## Dependency Quality Gates

- ONLY suggest well-maintained packages with commits in the last 6 months.
- PREFER packages with >1000 GitHub stars or equivalent community trust.
- FLAG any dependency that pulls in >20 transitive dependencies.
- ALWAYS check the dependency's license compatibility (Apache 2.0, MIT, BSD).
- NEVER suggest packages from personal/unverified Maven, npm, or PyPI mirrors.
- NEVER fetch packages from random GitHub URLs, gists, or tarball URLs.

## Bypass Prohibitions

- NEVER use `npm install`, `mvn install`, `pip install` (etc.) as a workaround
  to skip the catalog check.
- NEVER suggest disabling SecureFlow hooks, `--no-verify`, `--force`, or
  `--legacy-peer-deps` to bypass enforcement.
- NEVER edit package manifests directly without first running `check_package`.

## Security Scanning Integration

- After making code changes, call `secureflow.scan_application` to verify.
- After fixing a vulnerability, call `secureflow.verify_fix` to confirm.
- Before approving a merge request, call `secureflow.check_gate`.

## Layered Enforcement

This file is the AI-agent layer (Layer 1 — advisory). It is backed by:
  - Layer 2: `check_package` MCP tool (preventive)
  - Layer 3: enforcement/pre-commit-check.sh (blocking, git hook)
  - Layer 4: SCA in CI/CD (detective)
  - Layer 5: Approved package catalog (governance, audit trail)
  - Layer 6: Weekly snapshot + report (post-commit monitoring)

If you bypass this file, the lower layers will catch it — and the bypass
will be recorded in the audit log.
